04826nam a22007455i 9780812201475DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122014757 a10.9783/97808122014752doi  a(DE-B1597)449000  a(OCoLC)979577788  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN1811b.B76 2007eb 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a809.152221 aBrown, Jane K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Persistence of Allegory :bDrama and Neoclassicism from Shakespeare to Wagner /cJane K. Brown. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b21 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Claude's Allegories and Literary Neoclassicism -- tChapter 3. Secular Tragedy: Neoclassicism in the Sixteenth Century -- tChapter 4. Allegory and Passion: Latin Dramatic Forms in the Seventeenth Century -- tChapter 5. The Allegorical Idioms of the Illusionist Stage: Spectacle in the Seventeenth Century -- tChapter 6. Opera and Dance: The Revival of Greek Tragedy -- tChapter 7. The Greek Revival: German Classicism and the Recovery of Spoken Drama -- tChapter 8. Wagner and the Death of Gesamtkunstwerk -- tCoda: "This Insubstantial Pageant" -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an impressively comparative work, Jane K. Brown explores the tension in European drama between allegory and neoclassicism from the sixteenth through the nineteenth century. Imitation of nature is generally thought to triumph over religious allegory in the Elizabethan and French classical theater, a shift attributable to the recovery of Aristotle's Poetics in the Renaissance. But if Aristotle's terminology was rapidly assimilated, Brown demonstrates that change in dramatic practice took place only gradually and partially and that allegory was never fully cast off the stage. The book traces a complex history of neoclassicism in which new allegorical forms flourish and older ones are constantly revitalized. Brown reveals the allegorical survivals in the works of such major figures as Shakespeare, Calderón, Racine, Vondel, Metastasio, Goethe, and Wagner and reads tragedy, comedy, masque, opera, and school drama together rather than as separate developments. Throughout, she draws illuminating parallels to modes of representation in the visual arts.A work of broad interest to scholars, teachers, and students of theatrical form, The Persistence of Allegory presents a fundamental rethinking of the history of European drama.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEuropean dramaxHistory and criticism. 0aNeoclassicism (Literature)zEurope. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220147540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812201475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812201475/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041354-0  Penn Press eBook-Package Literature  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_P